    "83776887": {
      "title": "Methods to study bacterial invasion",
      "abstract": "Abstract The ability to invade host cells is an important virulence factor for many pathogenic bacteria. This dynamic interaction between the bacterium and the host cell can be studied by analyzing the entry of bacteria into cultured mammalian cells. The use of these in vitro model systems has revealed a complex array of bacterial and host cell factors that are involved in the invasion process. These factors usually differ between bacterial pathogens. This review outlines some of the methods used to study bacterial invasion, including quantitation of bacterial uptake, the use of polarized epithelial cells as model systems, and methods to probe the role of the host cell in bacterial internalization, including the involvement of signal transduction pathways and cytoskeletal proteins."
    }
